<HEADLINE> Solidarity Celebrated in Poland  </HEADLINE>
By MONIKA SCISLOWSKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   GDANSK, Poland (AP) -- Solidarity founder Lech Walesa and guests
including former British leader Margaret Thatcher gathered outside
the Gdansk shipyard Thursday for a ceremony marking the start of
the union's anti-communist crusade 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 Solidarity supporters massed at Solidarity Square,
where the movement was born, to watch Walesa lay a wreath at the
foot of a monument to shipyard workers killed by the communists.
</P>
<P>
   Under sunny skies, union members brought hundreds of Solidarity
banners and a military band played the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief address, Walesa thanked Solidarity members and
supporters, who in 1980 were on both sides of the shipyard gate,
for their efforts to change Poland.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted the workers were ''in a special way paying the
price of the changes'' they initiated 20 years ago, referring to
layoffs, unemployment and other painful side-effects of Poland's
transformation to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''All those who took part in the struggle ... should be proud,''
he said. ''But with pride comes responsibility. We must watch and
make sure that process initiated in August 1980 goes in the right
direction and does not degenerate.''
</P>
<P>
   At an outdoor Mass later, the head of the nation's Roman
Catholic Church, Cardinal Jozef Glemp, called Solidarity's victory
a ''miracle on the Baltic'' and urged Poles to cultivate the
union's traditional ideals of solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need solidarity ... we need unity among social groups like
20 years ago,'' Glemp said in his sermon, echoing the main theme of
the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Walesa, , Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and
other union leaders appealed for unity and an end to political
infighting within Solidarity, whose popularity has declined sharply
since the union-led bloc won the 1997 parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite economic growth and continuing reforms, which filled
stores and brought dlrs 40 billion in foreign investment, many
Poles are dissatisfied with growing unemployment and shrinking
social blanket.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremonies end three days of festivities in this Baltic port
city, where Solidarity signed the milestone Gdansk agreement with
the communists 20 years ago. The agreements, meant to bring more
freedom and better conditions for workers, ended a two-week
nationwide strike and the official recognition marked Solidarity's
birth.
</P>
<P>
   But Poland's communist rulers backed away from the deal in
December 1981 and tried to crush the union with martial law. It
took eight more years of steady resistance, and cost more than 100
lives, but Solidarity toppled the regime in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Among the foreign guests at the ceremony was Thatcher, whom the
Gdansk City Council bestowed honorary citizenship on last week,
along with former U.S. President Ronald Reagan, for supporting
Solidarity in its long struggle against communism.
</P>
<P>
   She left the ceremony early, however, without making any public
remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
