<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Welcomes Burundi Peace Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council on Thursday welcomed
Burundi's compromise peace deal as an ''important step'' towards
national reconciliation and urged the rebels who didn't sign to
stop fighting and join the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to the press, the council also encouraged the
negotiators at the Arusha, Tanzania, peace talks to step up their
efforts to find a compromise on outstanding issues and to devise a
timetable for carrying out the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Burundi President Pierre Buyoya, the Tutsi-led government and
army, as well as Hutu and Tutsi political parties signed a power
sharing accord Monday, paving the way for ending a 7-year civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, however, lacked details on when a cease-fire
should take place and who would lead a three year transitional
government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hutu rebels and four out of 10 Tutsi parties
refused to sign the document, despite pressure from former South
African President Nelson Mandela, who promised to obtain the
cease-fire later.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton attended the signing ceremony and urged the
rebel holdouts to sign.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the four Tutsi parties said they were ready to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Tutsis dominate the army and economy of Hutu-majority Burundi.
Civil war broke out in 1993 upon the assassination of Burundi's
first and only democratically elected president, a Hutu. Fighting
since then has killed 200,000 people in the nation of roughly 6
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
