<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressDavid Bellamy:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- David Bellamy, who helped create safer containers
for blood, died Tuesday of brain cancer. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   Bellamy's key role in the invention of plastic medical
containers made storage and transfer of fluids more sterile. The
containers reduced the risk of contaminants filtering in with air.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Bellamy went to work for Harvard professor and medical
inventor Dr. Carl Walter. Together, they conceived and developed
the first plastic containers for blood, which were lighter than
glass, non-breakable and collapsible.
</P>
<P>
   He later helped develop disposable dialysis products and
technology for frozen drug delivery.
Ted R. Brown:
</P>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The man who built the tower where the
world's first atomic bomb was detonated died Sunday. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who founded Brown Construction Company in 1935, said in a
1980 interview the World War II project in the southern New Mexico
desert where a bomb was detonated in 1945 was so secret he signed a
blank government contract for an amount of money to be filled in
later.
</P>
<P>
   His men built 45 miles of roads, several observation bunkers and
several towers.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also built 60 percent of Interstate 25 and about 40
percent of Interstate 40 in the state in the late 1950s and 1960s.
Theodore Deglin:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Theodore ''Ted'' Deglin, a longtime New York
publicist, died on Aug. 15. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Deglin was the director of public relations for Madison Square
Garden from 1935 until entering the Army in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Deglin founded the public relations firm
Deglin-Woods, which later became Ted Deglin and Associates. He was
the founder of New York's WBAI-FM and a member of the board of
directors of the United Services Organizations for the New York
metropolitan area from 1961 to 1995.
Bruce Giles:
</P>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Bruce Giles, executive editor of The
Tuscaloosa News and a longtime crusader for open government, died
Thursday of cancer. He was 53.
</P>
<P>
   Giles had been with The Tuscaloosa News for four years. Before
moving to Alabama, he was the managing editor at The Ledger of
Lakeland, Fla., and the Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune and held
various editing and reporting positions at The Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Giles was active in The Associated Press Managing Editors
association and served as chairman of the group's Freedom of
Information committee in 1997. He also served on the board of
directors of the First Amendment Foundation and the Alabama Press
Association.
</P>
<P>
   While in Miami, Giles and a colleague won the prestigious Green
Eyeshade Award, presented by the Atlanta chapter of the Society of
Professional Journalists, for a series on political campaign
contributions.
Janice Hardenburger:
</P>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) -- Sen. Janice Hardenburger, a longtime
Republican activist and strong supporter of local government, died
Thursday of lung cancer. She was 68.
</P>
<P>
   Hardenburger was chairwoman of the Senate Elections and Local
Government Committee. Among colleagues and constituents, she was
known for fighting for the rights of local government.
</P>
<P>
   During the 2000 session, she helped craft legislation to
strengthen the Kansas Open Records Act and to require more
disclosure of lobbyist gifts to lawmakers.
Rose Hobart:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actress Rose Hobart, who appeared in more
than 40 movies until her career was stopped by questioning by the
House Un-American Activities Committee, died Tuesday. She was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Hobart played the leading lady or ''other woman'' in movies
during the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   She may be best known for her role opposite Humphrey Bogart in
''Conflict'' in 1945. Hobart was the wife he schemed to kill in
order to romance her more alluring sister, played by Alexis Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Hobart was on the board of the Screen Actors Guild when she was
called before the House committee investigating communism. She was
an active participant in Actors Lab, which supporters of Sen.
Joseph McCarthy considered subversive.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hobart had signed a paper stating that she was not
and never had been a Communist, she was blacklisted.
</P>
<P>
   Her movie credits also included ''East of Borneo'' in 1931 and
''Bride of Vengeance'' in 1949.
Conrad Marca-Relli:
</P>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Conrad Marca-Relli, an Italian-American artist who
served as a link between the European avant-garde and American
abstract expressionism, died Tuesday of a heart attack. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest contribution came in the 1950s when he
revolutionized the medium of collage adding strips of canvas over
the canvas and painting them over in a subdued palette -- ''a
painting with oil and canvas,'' in one critic's words.
</P>
<P>
   Marca-Relli's style blended classicism with surrealism and some
of the playful improvisations of his abstract expressionist friends
like Willem de Kooning and Jackson Pollock. He was known for
creating monumental-sized collages.
Hussein Abdel Nasser:
</P>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Hussein Abdel Nasser, the youngest brother
of Gamal Abdel Nasser, Egypt's late ruler whose advocacy of
pan-Arabism made him a hero to many, died Wednesday of lung cancer.
He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein Abdel Nasser was an air force pilot before joining
EgyptAir, the national carrier where he worked until his death. He
was EgyptAir's chairman of the Japan and Far East branch.
</P>
<P>
   Gamal Abdel Nasser served as Egyptian president from 1956 until
his death in 1970.
John C.A. Watkins:
</P>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) -- John C.A. Watkins, the longest-serving
publisher of The Providence Journal and a decorated World War II
fighter pilot, died Wednesday of complications from a broken hip
and a stroke. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   He was credited with bringing the newspaper into a new era of
journalism, building morning edition sales, buying radio stations
and cable TV systems and building a national magazine-printing
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins was publisher of the Journal from 1954 to 1979 and held
several other posts with the paper, including chairman of the board
of The Providence Journal Co.
</P>
<P>
   Also under Watkins, the newspapers won a Pulitzer Prize in 1974
for national reporting when it broke a story about President
Nixon's small tax payments.
</P>
