<HEADLINE> 2nd Man Indicted in Theft of Oscars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A county grand jury has indicted a dock
worker in the March theft of 55 Academy Awards statuettes, months
after he was arrested and then released because of a lack of
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges Anthony Hart, 38, of La Puente with one
count of grand theft, Deputy District Attorney Susan Navas said
Thursday. Hart was released on his own recognizance after
surrendering to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hart is the second Roadway Express employee charged in
connection with the Oscar theft. He pleaded innocent during an
arraignment in early August.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Ledent, a former Roadway truck driver, pleaded no
contest in June to grand theft. He is to begin serving a six-month
jail term in December. Ledent, 38, testified before grand jurors in
the indictment against Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five gold-plated Oscar statuettes were manufactured in
Chicago and shipped to the Bell warehouse where the men worked on
March 8.
</P>
<P>
   Salvage man Willie Fulgear found 52 of the Oscars in a Los
Angeles trash bin after the disappearance was publicized. They were
found one week before the March 26 Academy Awards ceremony. Three
are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   Fulgear received a $50,000 reward from Roadway Express and two
tickets to the Academy Awards.
</P>
</TEXT>
