<HEADLINE> Criminal Complaints Vs. Pinochet Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- The number of criminal complaints against
Gen. Augusto Pinochet climbed to 170 Thursday with a claim that 23
people were tortured during his 1973-90 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint was filed by lawyer Eduardo Contreras with one of
the plaintiffs, Beatriz Miranda, who alleged that several now
retired military officers as responsible for the alleged ''brutal
torture'' in the early stage of Pinochet's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the 84-year-old Pinochet was stripped of his
congressional immunity, paving the way for a trial on one of the
complaints, which deals with ''the caravan of death.''
</P>
<P>
   The caravan was a military squad that executed 72 political
prisoners shortly after the coup. Nineteen of the victims remain
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The judge probing the case against Pinochet has set Oct. 9 as
the date for his, but defense lawyers are seeking to postpone the
legal procedures on health grounds.
</P>
<P>
   An official report compiled by the civilian government that
succeeded Pinochet established 3,197 people were killed or made
disappear for political reasons under Pinochet.
</P>
</TEXT>
