<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Searches Wen Ho Lee's Home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE ROCK, N.M. (AP) -- FBI agents searched the home of Wen Ho
Lee on Thursday as the former Los Alamos National Laboratory
scientist accused of security breaches waited in jail for his
expected release Friday on bail.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 FBI personnel spent a little more than 12 hours
searching the home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did complete the tasks mandated by the court order, and we
feel we did a thorough and professional job,'' agent Doug Beldon
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Hollander, one of Lee's attorneys, kept watch on the
search from inside Lee's home. She said agents had not seized any
evidence that she knew of.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're looking for any evidence of these crimes, the
allegedly missing seven tapes,'' she said, referring to unsecure
computer tapes containing restricted data that Lee was accused of
downloading. The defense insists the tapes were destroyed, but the
government wants proof.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole point of this search was so the government could be
assured that before Wen Ho Lee was released that there was nothing
(of a sensitive scientific nature) in the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, is accused of downloading restricted material about
nuclear weapons to unsecure computers, as well. He has been jailed
since Dec. 10, charged with 59 counts, and could face life in
prison if convicted. Trial is set Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney George Stamboulidis emphasized in court
Tuesday that until those tapes are located or proven destroyed,
there can be no adequate security measure for Lee's release.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge James Parker on Tuesday ordered that Lee be
released at noon Friday on $1 million bond. An appeal could still
delay Lee's release, but there was no word on any such filing
Thursday. The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver would
have to issue an emergency stay of Parker's order.
</P>
<P>
   Parker proposed what he described as ''highly restrictive
terms'' for Lee's release, including a search of the home, and
ordered prosecution and defense attorneys to negotiate the final
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The final conditions were not made public, but the judge's
proposal included limits on communication, travel, home visits and
required removal of all electronic communication devices except for
one telephone line. Lee would have to remain under electronic
monitoring and wear an electronic bracelet. His mail also could be
inspected. Lee's neighbors are to serve as his custodians during
his release.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the area around Lee's home was cordoned off by
police cars and cones. People were going in and out of the home,
some carrying clipboards.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lee's neighbors, Nora Aubert, said: ''I want it to be
over. I want them to release him or do something.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Lee: http://www.wenholee.org
</P>
<P>
   Department of Justice: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory: http://www.lanl.gov/worldview
</P>
</TEXT>
