<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Absent at UN Parliament Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States' absence from the first
meeting of parliamentary leaders of more than 140 countries is
being viewed as a sign of Washington's growing isolation from
global politics.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding officers of parliaments from China, Russia, Britain,
France and dozens of other countries flew thousands of miles to
attend the meeting. But U.S. Congress members, who had the shortest
distance to travel, were conspicuously absent.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who presides over the Senate, was
invited to the three-day conference that ends Friday. So were
Senate Majority leader Trent Lott and House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sent regrets that he would be campaigning for the
presidency, but Lott and Hastert never responded, said Anders
Johnsson, secretary-general of the Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU),
which organized the conference with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert went to Colombia on Wednesday with President Clinton and
had campaign commitments, spokesman John Feehery told The
Associated Press. Lott's press office never responded to queries
about his absence.
</P>
<P>
   The short shrift given to the conference by the congressional
leaders mirrors the change in the U.S. attitude toward the
Inter-Parliamentary Union, an organization that encourages
cooperation among the world's legislative bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was a founding member of the IPU in 1889 and
played a prominent role until the mid-1990s, when congressional
leaders cut back their participation, Johnsson said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which is assessed 15 percent of the IPU's
budget, also cut back payments. It paid nothing in 1998 and 1999
and now owes more than $2.4 million, according to IPU records. The
United States also owes more than $1.5 billion to the United
Nations, according to U.N. figures.
</P>
<P>
   Avraham Burg, speaker of Israel's Knesset, said Thursday that he
discussed the IPU a few weeks ago with Hastert, who is considering
advocating a U.S. pullout from the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do hope that America won't withdraw,'' Burg said. ''I do not
think it is good for the well-being of the world that the United
States of America is isolating itself from the political affairs
and the political flow of events of the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has an interest in keeping its staunchest ally in global
forums, especially at this critical time in the Middle East peace
process, Burg explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''Leaving Israel alone in this arena, I believe, stands against
the best interest of the United States of America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnsson said the end of the Cold War may have led ''to a
lessened interest in international cooperation'' by the United
States. He said that members of the U.S. Congress do want to be
active, but apparently not the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Robert Ney, an Ohio Republican who was part of a U.S.
congressional team that met informally with the speaker of the
Iranian parliament Wednesday night, said he couldn't understand the
American absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should participate,'' he said. ''I'm going to take it up
with the speaker. This is wrong we are not participating.''
</P>
<P>
   Some parliamentary participants also are miffed at the Clinton
Administration's decision to ban the speakers of the Cuban and
Yugoslav parliaments from entering the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was so angered at the refusal to grant visas to
Ricardo Alarcon, president of Cuba's National Assembly, and Srdja
Bozovic, president of the Yugoslav Federal Assembly's Chamber of
Republics, that it endorsed a statement Wednesday calling
Washington's action ''contrary to the principle underlying the
functioning of parliaments.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said the United
States does not have an obligation to the IPU to issue visas. But
Russia's Foreign Ministry and many visiting members of parliament
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that if a country agrees to allow an international
organization to meet on its territory, this does not give it a
right to determine the participants,'' said Lord Russell Johnston,
president of the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
