<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tight Race Expected for Bush  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER R. MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- While ''there's a campaign ebb and flow''
that lately has run against George W. Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee is where he expected to be at Labor Day, in a
tight contest with Vice President Al Gore, his chief strategist
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not doing anything different,'' said Karl Rove. ''This
is going to be a tight race. So what's new?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was campaigning Friday in Texarkana, Ark., and Lafayette,
La., concentrating on education, his chosen topic during a week of
campaign distractions. They included a ruling by a federal judge
demanding improvements in his state's handling of medical benefits
for low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   Rove, political director for Bush, acknowledged in an interview
Thursday that Gore has gained in the polls since the Democratic
National Convention, but noted he had publicly forecast that would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look, there's a campaign ebb and flow and this guy's had a
couple of good weeks,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   He juggled incoming calls on three telephones, stopped to shred
a sheaf of campaign papers left over from an earlier meeting and
called out instructions to aides as he said there's no sense of
alarm over the state of the race, in which Bush had held hefty
leads in the public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the boost Gore got from his convention is ebbing. ''We
fully expected this to tighten up and we expected to be behind in a
number of polls on Labor Day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the situation will level out and he doubted that
anything, including campaign debates still to be negotiated, would
vault either candidate far ahead of the other.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see it going up and down, but I don't see any dramatic
movement for anybody,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   That could make for an election that will turn on organization
and party efforts to get out the vote, especially in the swing
states of the Midwest, Rove said. He said the Bush campaign is
geared up to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said he isn't concerned about voter judgments of Bush based
on critiques and TV jokes over words he mispronounces or misuses,
or over the limited pace of his campaigning so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wouldn't be where he is if people did not think he was up
to the job,'' Rove said. He said they will have ample opportunity
to judge him for themselves because Bush will campaign more
aggressively after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''The key is when do you turn it on,'' he said. ''We're going to
power up.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's campaign was a two-stop affair, with Bush winding up at
his ranch near Crawford. He is receiving a CIA national security
briefing there Saturday, standard treatment for presidential
nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed as the work of ''an activist, liberal judge'' the
federal court ruling that Texas is not complying with a 1996 court
commitment to improve health care services for low-income children
under Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are doing everything in our power to take care of the
disadvantaged children of the state of Texas,'' Bush said Thursday
as he campaigned in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Texas state plans to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the federal government has refused to grant waivers
that would have made it easier to help needy children.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason they're pounding me is because this is an
administration of which Al Gore is a part that has been unable to
lead,'' he said. ''They're trying to go on the offensive on an
issue on which they are extremely vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, said
the ruling was troubling and that Bush ''has an obligation to
explain'' it.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee had planned to start airing TV
commercials criticizing the Texas record in Medicaid, but put them
on hold, in favor of complaining about a new Republican ad the Gore
camp denounces as negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   That one, to be broadcast in 17 states beginning as early as
Friday, challenges Gore's credibility with an image of his
appearance at a 1996 event at a Buddhist temple, and caustic
suggestions that he keeps reinventing himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
