<HEADLINE> Gore Pauses Before 'U.S. Workathon'  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore pauses only briefly before bursting
into a 24-hour ''American Workathon'' to mark the Labor Day holiday
with a presidential campaign blitz leading up to a major economic
speech, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides familiar with the plans who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Gore planned a five-city tour beginning Sunday to
''spend time with Americans who are working.''
</P>
<P>
   That was being followed by a speech Wednesday in Cleveland where
he was to offer a detailed economic plan with specific goals for
the country's economic future, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has gained in the polls since the Democratic National
Convention and he spent this week talking up a series of detailed
health care plans. He said voters are beginning to focus on those
issues and that's what has boosted him in the campaign against
Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the American people focus on issues and ask the candidates
for specifics, as I expected they would when we reached Labor Day,
that's what I most enjoy talking about,'' Gore told reporters
aboard his campaign plane Thursday. ''I'm in my element. I love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day marks the traditional opening of the fall campaign
season, and Gore was taking full advantage by launching ''a 24-hour
Labor Day Workathon, a nonstop, around-the-clock push to kick off
our ticket's economic agenda for America's future,'' aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Plans called for launching the blitz Sunday afternoon with
construction workers in Philadelphia, followed by a Flint, Mich.,
meeting with hospital workers, and a red-eye flight to Tampa, Fla.,
for a dawn meeting with firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters union was one of the first to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   From Florida, Gore dashes to Pittsburgh and Louisville, Ky., for
events showcasing middle-class workers.
</P>
<P>
   The swing is designed to make the point the Gore is a hard
worker, on a holiday to honor working Americans, and crank up the
intensity of an already hard-fought presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's week stays frantic, with him dashing to virtually every
region of the country despite a heavy focus on the industrial
Midwest, a key battleground in the election. The choice of
Cleveland as the site for his economic speech was no accident; Ohio
is a crucial battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has long argued that his economic proposals are better
designed to keep the economy prosperous. He pushes for smaller,
targeted tax cuts, as well as new spending on health care and
education, warning that Bush would plunge the nation back into
deficits with big tax cuts that mainly benefit the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Gore will offer a ''comprehensive economic agenda''
fleshing out even more specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've given specifics for every proposal, and we'll continue
to do that,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that while both campaigns have been running at a fever
pitch, Labor Day marks an important symbolic crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   ''Labor day begins a two-month home stretch for the campaign,''
Gore said. ''I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Democratic convention, most polls have shown Gore
gaining ground on Bush, and the two rivals are entering the
campaign's final sprint locked in a very close and competitive
race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you I'm feeling a lot more responsiveness and
enthusiasm and energy,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee hoped to turn things around
with new television commercials questioning Gore's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Gore rejected suggestions that the campaign had taken a
permanent turn for the negative.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't turn it into that,'' said Gore. ''I certainly hope it
doesn't turn into that.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on the new RNC spots, saying running mate
Joseph Lieberman had already addressed the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
