<DOCNO> APW20000901.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NJ--Indian Gambling. Also moving on national lines.  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   To measure the impact of the 1990s casino gambling
boom on
Indian reservations, The Associated Press obtained data from
federal agencies that measure employment, poverty and public
assistance.
<TEXT>
<P>
   AP divided reservations into two groups: those that operated a
Las-Vegas style casino under a Class III gaming license with the
state, and those that did not.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Class III casinos was provided by the National
Indian Gaming Association. Bingo parlors and other non-Class III
gaming operations were not included in the analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Counties with gaming and non-gaming tribes were compared, using
the Census Bureau's 1989 and 1995 income and poverty estimates, and
the 1990 and 1997 County Business Patterns data.
</P>
<P>
   Gaming and non-gaming tribes also were compared using 1991 and
1997 reservation unemployment estimates compiled by the Bureau of
Indian Affairs and Agriculture Department records detailing
participation in the Food Distribution Program on Indian
Reservations during the 1990s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-01-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000901.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
