<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Tradition Develops  </HEADLINE>
By MIRANDA LEITSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The 12 young men and women grip their paddles,
angling them just above the water and awaiting the start. They have
sweated and strained nine weeks for this moment -- their first
dragon boat race.
</P>
<P>
   The start signal blares, and the team storms across Meadow Lake
in its 2,000-pound boat decorated with a red dragon's head and
tail.
</P>
<P>
   Cries of ''Paddle! Paddle! Go! Go!'' mix with drum beats,
resounding over the lake.
</P>
<P>
   The race is over in less than four minutes. The Xtreme NY club
places third and Carol Chang, the team's drummer, who sets the
paddlers' pace, leads the dripping-wet crew in a cheer:
''Extreme!''
</P>
<P>
   The paddlers at the Hong Kong dragon boat festival in New York's
borough of Queens in mid-August were vying in the ancient Chinese
sport of dragon boating, which is attracting new adherents across
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   From San Francisco to New York, and along the Mississippi River
in places as unlikely as Dubuque, Iowa, more than 400 teams are
dragon boating, said Iowan Gary Carstens of the United States
Dragon Boat Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Most dragon boating hotspots are in the Midwest, which has 275
teams. Nearly 70 teams train in New York City, and some 80 teams
practice in and around Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love it. I want to win as much as anybody else, but I love
the team community,'' said Ginny O'Hare, 33, co-captain of New
York's Wall Street Lions crew.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is very, very hard ... but it's a great workout on the
river,'' said Ellen Tacelosky, 32, a banker from Arlington, Va.,
whose D.C. Dragons team paddles on Washington's Anacostia River.
</P>
<P>
   The key to a competitive team -- which traditionally has 18
paddlers, a steerer and a drummer -- is synchronization.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the paddles combine as one big paddle, and that's what
moves the boat forward,'' said Xtreme NY co-captain Kang Ko, 30, of
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it's a matter of speed. Paddlers use a combination
of strokes to propel the 38-foot canoes. Sharp slices through the
water make for a quick start or a run for the finish; deeper pulls
maintain a steady pace.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is attracting considerable interest outside the Asian
community.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of the sport is the promotion of Asian culture,'' said
Tim Woo, 37, of Queens. But ''even in New York, where I would say
you have the highest Asian-American participation, it's only 30 to
40 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragon boating began in China with the legend of Qu Yuan, a
poet-statesman who drowned himself in the Milo River in Central
Hunan province more than 2,000 years ago to protest government
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Qu's bereaved countrymen rowed boats in the river, beating their
paddles against the water to frighten fish and dragons away from
his body.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is part of our lives,'' said May Wong, a Hong Kong native
living in New York. ''I like it because it brings out Chinese
traditions and Americans can join in. They can learn something
about the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to trace the roots of the sport in the United
States. A Philadelphia rowing team was given a dragon boat in 1983
by a Hong Kong group, said Bill Toole of the Philadelphia dragon
boat team. A dragon boat festival in New York in 1991 -- sponsored
by a Hong Kong group -- sparked further interest.
</P>
<P>
   Paddlers say one reason for the growing participation in the
sport is that it requires relatively little skill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only so many people can play soccer, rugby or baseball, but
everyone can paddle,'' said Carstens, 48.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a team in Cedar Rapids where the youngest person is
62,'' said Carstens. ''Their motto is: 'We can do everything for a
minute and a half.'''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   United States Dragon Boat Federation: http://www.usdbf.com
</P>
<P>
   Xtreme NY: http://www.xtremeny.com
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Dragon Boat Association: http://www.hkdbf-ny.org
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Dragon Boat Association: http://www.battan.com/pdba
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
