<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor Crimes Suspects Named  </HEADLINE>
By IRWAN FIRDAUS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- State prosecutors named 19 army and
police officers, government officials and pro-Indonesian militiamen
on Friday as suspects in last year's rampant slayings and
destruction in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But former military commander Gen. Wiranto and prominent militia
leader Eurico Guterres, who have been implicated in the violence by
the United Nations and an earlier Indonesian inquiry, were absent
from the list.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, commanded
the armed forces during a militia rampage that followed the
U.N.-organized referendum on Aug. 30, 1999, in which the people of
East Timor voted overwhelmingly to separate from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   The decision not to take action against Wiranto -- who enjoys the
backing of powerful army hard-liners -- will likely result in
renewed calls for an international tribunal to bring the
perpetrators of the violence to justice.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's democratic government has rejected the idea of a
tribunal along the lines of those for Rwanda and the former
Yugoslavia. It insists its own court system is capable of bringing
those responsible to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Rachman, who leads the Indonesian joint commission on
human rights violations in East Timor, said Maj. Gen. Adam Damiri,
a former regional army commander, topped the list of possible
suspects, along with two brigadier generals.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven more officers, ranging from lieutenant to colonel, were
also named. Others on the list were Abilio Soares, East Timor's
former Indonesian-appointed governor, the district head of Liquica
township and three militia members.
</P>
<P>
   ''All will be summoned for questioning next week,'' Rachman
said.
</P>
<P>
   The group is accused in five specific atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   They include massacres in April 1999 of independence supporters
in Liquica and of refugees who sought shelter at the Dili home of
prominent independence leader Manuel Carrascalao.
</P>
<P>
   The group also is accused in violence that raged in the days
after the territory voted for independence last year -- including a
bloody attack on the home of East Timor's Nobel Peace laureate,
Roman Catholic Bishop Carlos Belo, killings in the border town of
Suai and the murder of Dutch journalist Sander Thoenes.
</P>
<P>
   East Timor's other Nobel Peace Prize winner, Jose Ramos-Horta,
was angered by the absence of Guterres from the suspects' list.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Eurico Guterres, a notorious war criminal, is not brought
to trial, it leaves no option to the United Nations but to set up a
war crimes tribunal,'' he said Friday in the capital, Dili.
</P>
<P>
   Guterres, who headed the notorious Aitarak (Thorn) militia, is
accused of leading the destruction of Dili. Just days before the
referendum, he publicly threatened to transform the town into ''a
sea of fire'' if its people voted for independence.
</P>
<P>
   At least 250 people died after the vote. Human rights groups
blame the Indonesian military for inciting the violence.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier Indonesian government-sponsored human rights
commission accused 33 military officers -- including Wiranto -- of
''crimes against humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   A separate U.N. panel concluded that the terror campaign ''would
not have been possible without the active involvement of the
Indonesian army, and the knowledge and approval of the top military
command.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, these findings forced President Abdurrahman
Wahid to fire Wiranto from his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto has admitted that some lower-ranking members of
Indonesia's military backed the militias, but has denied that the
army command actively supported the violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
