<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcanic Japanese Island Evacuated  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT STODDARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- All remaining residents of a Japanese island where
a volcano began erupting nearly two months ago were ordered to
evacuate Friday because of the danger of more eruptions,
earthquakes and landslides.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 residents had remained on Miyake Island, south of
Tokyo, since Mount Oyama rumbled back to life in early July. Only
police, fire and municipal personnel -- about 600 people -- will
remain there after Friday, said Keita Takashima, a Tokyo government
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation order comes two days after the 2,686-foot volcano
erupted for the eighth time in two months. More than 60 percent of
Miyake's residents had left the island voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The eruptions have blanketed the island with ash, prompting
warnings that heavy rains could set off mudslides. The island also
has been shaken by thousands of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has become a dangerous place, so it would be a relief to
leave,'' said Miyake government spokeswoman Izumi Asanuma, who was
awaiting a decision about whether she would be evacuated. Her
mother and two brothers have already left, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Government shelters have been set up in Tokyo and ships were
dispatched to the island to help evacuate the remaining residents.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, 13,000 people were ordered to evacuate in
northern Japan after Mount Usu erupted for the first time in 22
years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, all 10,000 residents on Oshima Island in the Izu Island
chain were evacuated for a month after Mount Mihara erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have said shifts in huge underground pools of magma are
responsible for the recent volcanic and seismic activity on Miyake,
which is about 120 miles south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquakes that have rocked Miyake and surrounding islands
in the Izu chain have generated fears a big earthquake could strike
Tokyo. The capital, also highly vulnerable, on Friday marked the
anniversary of a 1923 earthquake that killed 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori and about 5.5 million people across
the nation took part in annual drills to commemorate the quake.
They culminate Sunday with a massive military rescue exercise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
