<HEADLINE> Couple Jailed for Falsifying Drug  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A husband and wife involved in testing a
cancer drug have been sentenced to prison for falsifying results
that helped the drug win federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   Harry W. Snyder was sentenced Thursday in federal court to three
years in prison and his wife, Renee Peugeot, to 2&AMP;frac12; years for
conspiracy, mail fraud and making false statements to the Food and
Drug Administration. They were also ordered to make restitution of
$26,000 to the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   A jury in March found that the couple falsified data from
clinical trials conducted between 1994 and 1995 on BCX-34, an
experimental drug to treat psoriasis and skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the two planned to cash in when the company's
stock prices rose on news of the drug's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, a former BioCryst Pharmaceuticals Inc. vice president,
oversaw clinical development. Peugeot was a nurse who helped run
the drug trials.
</P>
<P>
   BioCryst reported the irregularities to the FDA in 1995 and
admitted that earlier test results were misleading. At the time the
Snyders were indicted, BioCryst said authorities made assurances
that neither the company nor any other employee would be targeted
in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The judge allowed the pair, now Texas residents, to remain out
on bond pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very complicated, lengthy case,'' said defense lawyer
Mark White. ''We feel confident on appeal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
