<HEADLINE> David Schwimmer Makes Theater Plea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- David Schwimmer is issuing a challenge grant of
''maybe around $250,000'' to fund a new home for the theater
company he helped found more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schwimmer called the Lookingglass Theater ''my home, my family,
my brothers and sisters'' at a Thursday news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel I am most challenged and fulfilled when I'm working
with this company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member company is considered one of Chicago's prime
small-theater companies and was founded in 1988 by Northwestern
University graduates.
</P>
<P>
   The Lookingglass' new home will be in the landmark Water Tower
and Pumping Station on Chicago's Magnificent Mile. The city and
state each will provide $1.5 million to the $6.5 million
renovation. The rest of the money will come from Lookingglass
fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is scheduled to begin later this year, with the
theater doors to open in 2002.
</P>
