<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dr. T and the Women' Premieres  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENICE, Italy (AP) -- Director Robert Altman and star Richard
Gere were girding themselves for flak about political correctness
with the world premiere Friday of ''Dr. T and the Women'' at the
Venice Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Skewering yet another slice of Americana, Altman tells the tale
of a Dallas gynecologist awash in a sea of idle, affluent women --
wives, daughters, lovers, mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The comedy bears all the trademarks of the man who directed
''MASH,'' ''McCabe &AMP; Mrs. Miller,'' ''Nashville'' and ''The
Player'': ensemble acting at its freshest with a sharp satirical
bite and a dash of the surreal.
</P>
<P>
   The vast cast includes Helen Hunt, Shelley Long, Laura Dern, Liv
Tyler, Farah Fawcett, a bunch of Dallas Cowboy cheerleaders and a
bevy of real-life shop-a-holic society matrons.
</P>
<P>
   Gere plays Dr. Sullivan Travis, a man who loves women but really
doesn't understand them. He is awash in the female sex, both
professionally and personally. His waiting room is always packed
with dressed-to-the-nines neurotics.
</P>
<P>
   At home, his wife (Fawcett) has regressed into a childlike state
-- a victim of too much pampering and too much love -- on the eve of
their cheerleader daughter's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the chaos, Dr. T's champagne-swilling sister (Dern)
and her three little girls have just moved in with him. Meanwhile,
Dr. T's other daughter, a Kennedy conspiracy buff, thinks something
is amiss in the choice of the maid of honor (Tyler).
</P>
<P>
   At lunch before the black-tie premiere, Altman and Gere rallied
to the defense of the movie and what Altman called ''all these
questions about being politically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People say, 'You made them all foolish women. Do you think all
women are that way?''' He paused over his pasta. ''I think some
women have to present themselves that way because that's what the
culture demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. T both exaggerates and embraces the women who inhabit a very
particular strata of American life and what Altman described as a
''very weird place.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, he said, is ''known for two things: the Dallas Cowboy
cheerleaders and the Kennedy assassination. There's nothing else in
Dallas other than shopping -- and women in silly hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Gere's character loves these women. He pampers the women in his
life, both professional and personal, and when things go wrong, he
fixes them. But he really doesn't understand them.
</P>
<P>
   ''For most of his life, he's been looking at them from the wrong
angle,'' Altman joked of his gynecologist-protagonist.
</P>
<P>
   Gere said he accepted the role immediately after he read the
screenplay. He was so eager to work with Altman that he did it
without a salary, taking a cut of any profits instead.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hollywood's most stalwartly independent filmmakers,
Altman makes movies on a tight budget; ''Dr. T'' cost just $16
million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. T,'' one of 20 films in competition at the Venice Film
Festival, is slated for release in the United States in October and
worldwide in December.
</P>
<P>
   Venice has been good to Altman over the years; in 1996, it gave
him the coveted Golden Lion award for lifetime achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old director was nominated for Oscars for ''MASH''
in 1970, ''Nashville'' in 1975 and ''Short Cuts'' in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-01-00 1432 </TRAILER>
