<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Newspaper Editor Resigns  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The civilian editor of the Stars &AMP; Stripes
newspaper, a government publication aimed at U.S. troops abroad,
resigned Friday to protest what he called Pentagon pressure to kill
a news story.
</P>
<P>
   The story, which had been prepared for Friday editions of the
Stars &AMP; Stripes, was essentially the same as an article published
on the front page of Friday's Washington Post, Stars &AMP; Stripes
executive editor David Offer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Post reported that the Army had alerted a Patriot
anti-missile unit in Germany to be prepared for possible deployment
to Israel, reflecting U.S. government concern that Iraq might
attack Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Offer said Army public affairs officers in Germany told him they
did not dispute the accuracy of the story.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, however, said the story should not run because it
contained classified information, according to Thomas E. Kelsch,
the civilian publisher of Stars &AMP; Stripes. Kelsch gave the order to
kill the story.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsch, who has a top-secret clearance, said he could not
discuss the objectionable material because of secrecy rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand behind my decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What troubled both Kelsch and Offer was that Stars &AMP; Stripes
ended up publishing the Post story in subsequent editions, even
though it contained the same information. Offer said he had argued
at that point that the Stripes' own version should be run, since
the Post story had already been published. Kelsch, however, said he
followed a Pentagon directive which prohibits Stripes from
knowingly publishing classified information but does not stop it
from running such stories generated by commercial newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes no sense to me,'' Kelsch said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Offer said that although he was upset at the initial decision to
kill the Stripes' own story, he felt compelled to resign when the
paper was not allowed to run it even after the Post published the
same information.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absurd and it's unacceptable,'' he said in an interview.
''This is news management by the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Offer, 58, was editor of the Newport Daily News in Rhode Island
for 12 years before taking the Stripes job five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The article, written by Stripes staff reporter Jon R. Anderson,
raised ''national security concerns'' and therefore could not be
published, according to Kelsch, who five months ago became Stars &AMP;
Stripes' first civilian publisher. It previously had been run by
military commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was requested to do this'' by Pentagon officials, Kelsch
said. ''I was not ordered.'' He said he could have chosen to run
the story over Pentagon objections, but added, ''I don't know what
would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the request came through Clifford Bernath, director of
the Armed Forces Information Service, a Pentagon office that sets
policy for Stars &AMP; Stripes but is not supposed to interfere with
editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Bernath said the decision to kill the story was
Kelsch's, although he discussed the matter with him at length after
learning through ''Army channels'' that Stripes planned to publish
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Bernath said the prohibition on publishing government secrets is
logical. ''We can't publish it -- we're the government.''
</P>
<P>
   The government owns Stars &AMP; Stripes, which is published only for
troops deployed abroad. The Pentagon pays about one-third of the
newspaper's budget; the bulk of the rest of its revenue is from
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsch said he was upset by Offer's decision to quit. ''It's
awful. It's a serious loss to our organization. He said he hoped
the incident would lead to changes in the newspaper's relationship
with the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are still in the growing pains of becoming a fully free and
fully civilianized paper,'' Kelsch said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Department of Defense: http://www.defenselink.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
