<HEADLINE> State Colleagues Remember Courier  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A memorial service was held Friday at the
State Department for a 31-year-old diplomatic courier killed in
last week's crash into the Persian Gulf of a Gulf Air jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   The courier, Seth J. Foti, was among 143 passengers and crew who
died when the Airbus 320 nose-dived into the water as it tried to
land in Manama, Bahrain, on a flight from Cairo, Egypt. Foti was
carrying classified material, which was lost in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Foti's wife, Anisha; his mother, Deyann; his father, Dominick;
and his stepfather, Max, attended Friday's ceremony in the State
Department lobby. A plaque to honor Foti was placed on a wall along
with others who died in their country's foreign service.
</P>
<P>
   Foti, who become a courier only 14 months ago, was praised by
Undersecretary of State Bonnie Cohen, who said he ''quickly
distinguished himself as a true professional. He understood the
importance of his tasks and performed them confidently.''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic couriers carry classified material throughout the
network of U.S. diplomatic missions. Foti was one of 97 American
couriers. Six other couriers have died in crashes, the last in
1963.
</P>
</TEXT>
