<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin Grammys To Be Braodcast Live  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The first Latin Grammys show, to be broadcast
live on network television this month, has been touted as a means
of bringing Latin music to a primetime audience.
</P>
<P>
   But it has angered some who claim it celebrates what has made
the music so popular among non-Latins -- crossover artists like
Ricky Martin -- at the expense of less-flashy regional styles.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement this week of the nominations by the Latin
Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences produced a boycott threat from
a Latin music label and the criticism of at least one artist who
said there aren't enough popular Mexican styles -- like norteno,
tejano and ranchera -- nominated for the biggest awards.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Estefan Jr., who is married to singer Gloria Estefan and
nominated for six Latin Grammys for his work as a producer of
various artists, rebuked those who criticized the event.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a time when we should be celebrating the coming
together of our culture and musical heritage, not creating barriers
that we as a Latino community have fought so hard against in our
quest for the American dream,'' said Estefan, a Cuban exile.
</P>
<P>
   The criticisms came primarily from Fonovisa, which is owned by
Mexican media giant Grupo Televisa and is the nation's largest
Spanish-language music label. The label admitted last year to
paying more than $1 million to radio programmers in a payola
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Fonovisa sees a slant against Mexican music, even though
Mexicans represent a majority of Hispanics in the United States.
Pepe Aguilar, a ranchera singer, said he would boycott the ceremony
because the lack of Mexican regional artists nominated in major
categories.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers for the Latin Grammys, scheduled to be broadcast
Sept. 13 on CBS, dismiss the charges. They insist the nominations
of Spanish- and Portuguese-language artists are representative.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our process is beyond reproach. (The Latin Grammys) has
nominations which reflect a diverse population of Latin music,''
said Adam Sandler, an academy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Latin music has experienced a boom among non-Hispanics in the
past two years, with artists such as Martin, Marc Anthony, Jennifer
Lopez and Enrique Iglesias combining to sell millions of records
and generate numerous hits on the pop charts. Santana won a
record-tying eight Grammys earlier this year at the Grammys for his
multiplatinum ''Supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   Artists nominated for the Latin Grammys' record of the year
include Martin, Anthony, Ruben Blades, Carlos Vives and Santana
with the band Mana. Lopez and Christina Aguilera were nominated in
other categories.
</P>
<P>
   During the show, 'N Sync will perform a duet with Son By Four, a
Puerto Rican salsa band, in another move to appeal to both Latino
and non-Latino audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The nominations were determined by the academy's 4,000 members.
In several major categories, including record of the year, academy
members nominated artists who are easily recognizable to
non-Hispanic music fans.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will celebrate a diversity of genres, including pop,
rock, salsa, tropical, tejano, norteno, tango, jazz, classical,
merengue, and flamenco. Fonovisa, however, says the nominations
ignore its artists' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Fonovisa's general manager, Gilberto Moreno, told the
Spanish-language newspaper La Opinion that artists associated with
Sony Music's labels and Miami-based producer Estefan were favored
over stars who appeal to specific ethnic communities, particularly
Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   Only five Fonovisa artists -- Los Tigres del Norte and Banda El
Recodo among them -- have been nominated among the estimated 200
nominees. All the label's nominees are in the Mexican regional
field.
</P>
<P>
   Los Tigres del Norte have enjoyed commercial success, along with
a fervent, loyal following among immigrant communities. During
their 30-year career, they have performed in front of 100,000
people at a time in Los Angeles, Monterrey and Guatemala City. The
band has made 30 records and 14 movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Nuys-based Fonovisa label urged its artists to avoid the
ceremony, but it was unclear if any were going to follow suit.
Sandler said he was unable to get in contact with Moreno, but had
spoken with some Fonovisa acts, including Marco Antonio Solis, and
said they planned to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second controversy surrounding the Latin Grammys.
Organizers had considered holding the show in Miami, but the
Miami-Dade county's anti-Cuba ban would have prevented Cuban
artists from performing, and knocked the city out of the running.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Grammys: http://www.grammys.com
</P>
<P>
   Latin Grammys: http://www.grammy.com/laras/
</P>
</TEXT>
