<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Testimony on White House E-Mails  </HEADLINE>
By OWEN S. GOOD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former deputy White House counsel Cheryl Mills
testified Friday she did not speak with President Clinton or senior
aides about a computer error that kept her office from reviewing
thousands of e-mail messages under subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   She also indicated she took a hands-off role in overseeing a
1998 search to determine if the glitch prevented subpoenaed e-mails
from being turned over to investigators in the Monica Lewinsky
case.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative legal group Judicial Watch, which brought the
lawsuit that uncovered the missing e-mails, contends the White
House knew the scope of the problem and found it a convenient
excuse for not turning over e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   White House witnesses have said a ''disconnect'' between lawyers
and technicians left the legal staff unaware of the matter's
severity.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Royce Lamberth has been holding
hearings for several weeks to determine how to retrieve the
thousands of messages that were not properly archived from
September 1996 to November 1998. Technicians are now trying to
restore the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said she assigned White House lawyer Michelle Peterson in
June 1998 to compare messages submitted to Independent Counsel Ken
Starr's office with ones produced by another search by technicians
of White House e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers wanted to determine if that second search
had produced missing messages under subpoena; they found none.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said she did not know how the technicians' search was
performed or what e-mail accounts it included. She said she did not
give Peterson specific instructions on how to compare messages.
</P>
<P>
   Mills also said she told her boss, White House counsel Charles
Ruff, of the findings, but did not put it in the form of a written
report.
</P>
<P>
   Mills' testimony frustrated attempts by her questioner, Judicial
Watch lawyer Larry Klayman, to portray the test as willfully
slipshod and designed to produce an answer her office wanted to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   ''You didn't want to know'' if e-mails hadn't been turned over,
Klayman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't agree with that characterization,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Klayman also sought to link knowledge of the problem and the
faulty test to Clinton, insinuating she was close to the president
because he recommended her for White House counsel, a job she
turned down. Mills left the White House last October.
</P>
<P>
   Mills said she could not recall talking with White House chief
of staff John Podesta about the problem. Her conversations about
the missing e-mails were limited to Peterson and Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   The computer problems became public in February in a $90 million
class-action suit filed by Judicial Watch, which has filed several
lawsuits against Clinton since 1994. The lawsuit involves FBI
background files gathered in the White House on hundreds of
appointees from the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth recessed the hearing for at least a week, and will make
a decision later to either close the hearing or bring in more
witnesses. Klayman wants to question White House chief of staff
John Podesta and Virginia Apuzzo, the former assistant t the
president for management and administration.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberth indicated his decision may come before Sept. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
