<HEADLINE> Exception Sought on Reagan Monument  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A prominent site in the center of the capital
for a monument to former President Reagan will be discussed at an
official hearing Tuesday despite an agreement by federal
commissions that there should be no more memorials in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The exception is sought in a bill introduced by Rep. Don Young,
R-Alaska. It will be taken up by the National Capital Memorial
Commission. The bill, now before the House Resources Committee,
would direct the commission to make an exception to the moratorium
on new memorials ''for a future memorial'' to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, joined in introducing the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Memorial Commission and two others, the Fine Arts Commission
and the National Capital Planning Commission, agreed last year not
to approve any new memorials in an area called The Reserve. That
includes the Mall -- the long grassy sweep from the Capitol to the
Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Exceptions were made for monuments already approved, including a
World War II memorial and one to Martin Luther King Jr. Plans for
them are going forward, though last month two dozen witnesses
appeared to oppose the site and design for the war memorial at a
public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Young's bill would order Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and
his successors to pick a spot and a design for the Reagan monument,
raise donations to build it and create a three-person commission to
help.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan, now 89, left office in 1989 after serving two terms. In
1994, he published a letter addressed to the American people
disclosing that he suffered from Alzheimer's disease. A major new
government building on Pennsylvania Avenue has been named for him
and National Airport has been renamed in his honor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-01-00 2010 </TRAILER>
