<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House To SmithKline: Turn in Info  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A congressional committee has ordered
SmithKline Beecham to turn over documents detailing how it
determines the prices of Kytril, a drug used to prevent nausea in
cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   The House Commerce Committee is investigating drug pricing
because of a Department of Health and Human Services report that
concluded that Medicare could have saved $447 million if prices had
been lower.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter Friday to SmithKline chief executive Jean-Pierre
Garnier, committee chairman Tom Bliley set a deadline of noon
Tuesday for the company to produce the documents. If the files are
not in the committee's hands, the panel could subpoena them,
Bliley, R-Va., wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman SmithKline, whose U.S. headquarters are in
Philadelphia, did not immediately return a phone call seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   HHS' Office of Inspector General concluded that the Health Care
Financing Administration pays more for 22 drugs, including Kytril,
because those companies charge higher prices to physicians being
reimbursed by Medicare than they do the wholesale price.
</P>
<P>
   As a follow-up to the report, the committee requested pricing
information from SmithKline and six other companies on May 4.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline has submitted ''several'' boxes of documents but the
committee is still waiting for 11 documents, which focus on
reimbursement procedures, marketing plans and pricing, Sheffield
said.
</P>
<P>
   On August 14 the company said it would not turn over those
documents because they are protected by attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's letter, Bliley wrote that congressional committees
are not obligated to recognize attorney-client privilege.
</P>
<P>
   SmithKline announced Thursday that it would sell Kytril to Roche
AG, of Switzerland, for $1.23 billion in cash. The divestiture is
part of SmithKline's effort to win regulatory approval for its
pending $75 billion merger with another British drug maker, Glaxo
Wellcome. The deal, which has been approved by shareholders of each
company, is scheduled to close on Sept. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
