<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Cut Short Vacation Trip  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton began his Labor Day
weekend tasting barbecue at a fund-raiser where he depicted Hillary
Rodham Clinton as a prominent woman on the world stage who has a
lot to offer New Yorkers if they make her their senator.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everywhere I go in the world, people I don't even know come to
me and say 'I am pulling for your wife. I'm sorry she can't be
here,''' Clinton said at the Friday night fund-raiser that raised
$110,000 for her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a state dinner last month in Africa, the president of Nigeria
declared his support for Mrs. Clinton. On a trip to India, a woman
in Bombay spoke only of Mrs. Clinton, not of the work she is doing
to help Indian women improve their lives, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's daughter, Chelsea, has accompanied him on recent
foreign trips, but the Clintons decided to cut short their visit to
upstate New York and spend time with Chelsea, who is nursing a
summer cold.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser was held at the Tudor style home of John Duke
Kinney, a childhood friend of top Democratic fund-raiser, Terry
McAuliffe. With high hopes that Mrs. Clinton will win a Senate seat
from New York, the Kinneys posted a sign on their garage that read:
''Welcome Senator &AMP; President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   About 100 guests, who each were asked to contribute $1,000, were
served pulled pork, spareribs, chicken, baked beans, salad and
potatoes catered by a Syracuse restaurant called ''The Dinosaur.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very famous. Best ribs in the country,'' McAuliffe said
he told Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Being from Arkansas, the president initially disputed that, but
after dinner said: ''I come from a place where barbecue is not
food, it is a way of life. It is a philosophy of human nature. I
have rarely had anything as good as this.''
</P>
<P>
   The president intends to play golf on Saturday with McAuliffe
and others including Tom Scherrer, a 29-year-old Syracuse native
who in June won the Kemper Open golf tournament in Maryland. Also
Saturday, he plans to attend a fund-raiser for his wife in
Cazenovia, also in the Finger Lakes region of New York, and meet up
with her at the state fair, where the rock group Goo Goo Dolls is
playing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a restaurateur in nearby Skaneateles, N.Y., where the
Clintons are staying overnight, began selling a bologna sandwich in
a swipe against the first lady. This year, the first couple
received a warm welcome at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred people greeted them Friday at the airport in
Syracuse, where they were serenaded on the tarmac by a male a
cappella group, who sang ''The Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope all of you are registered to vote,'' Mrs. Clinton said.
A sign in the crowd read: ''Bill, shake my hand. Eight great
years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons planned to return Saturday night to Washington.
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Chelsea, 20, who
accompanied her father on trips last week to Africa and Colombia,
originally wanted to join her parents in New York but was too worn
from her travels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the African trip, the day trip to Colombia, and a
little bit of a head cold has led her to decide she'd rather just
stay around the house here in Washington this weekend,'' Lockhart
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
